# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Builder Pattern (GoF Creational Pattern):** The Builder Method is a creational design pattern that **separates the construction of a complex object from its representation**, allowing the same construction process to create different representations. It builds an object **step-by-step** through a sequence of method calls on a builder object, with the final object being retrieved via a `getResult()` (or similar) method.

According to the **Gang of Four (GoF)** classification that KTU follows in PECGT411:
- **Category:** Creational Design Pattern
- **Intent:** Encapsulate object construction so that the same process can yield different object types/representations.
- **Problem Solved:** The *Telescoping Constructor Anti-Pattern* (constructors with too many optional parameters).

> [!NOTE]
> **Syllabus Highlight (Module 4 – Design Patterns):** The Builder Pattern is a high-weightage topic in KTU 2024 Scheme ESE (End Semester Examination). Students are expected to draw the **UML Class Diagram**, identify **participants**, explain **collaborations**, and write a **small implementation skeleton (Java/C++/Python pseudocode)** in the answer sheet.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition (Plain English)

Imagine you walk into a **Domino's Pizza** outlet 🍕.

You don't hand the cashier a pre-cooked pizza. Instead, you say:
- *"Crust: Thin"*
- *"Size: Medium"*
- *"Cheese: Extra"*
- *"Toppings: Mushroom, Olives, Paneer"*

The cashier passes this configuration to the **kitchen (Builder)**, which assembles the pizza **step-by-step** in the correct order. You get back your fully-baked custom pizza.

**Key insight:** The process of *making* a pizza is **separated** from the *recipe* (representation). Tomorrow, if you order a "Thick Crust, Large, Farmhouse", the same process works — but the resulting pizza is different.

| Real-World Analogy | Software Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Pizza outlet ordering process | **Director** (Client orchestration logic) |
| Step-by-step customization | **Builder interface** (setCrust, setSize, setCheese...) |
| Kitchen assembling pizza | **ConcreteBuilder** (HawaiianBuilder, FarmhouseBuilder) |
| Final Pizza on the table | **Product** (the complex object) |

> [!TIP]
> **Mnemonic for KTU Exam — "PDBC":** **P**roduct, **D**irector, **B**uilder, **C**oncreteBuilder. Memorize the 4 participants in this order.

---

## 1.3 Key Terminology (Bold Definitions for High-Yield Recall)

- **Product (`Product`):** The complex object that is being constructed. It is typically composed of multiple parts.
- **Builder (`Builder`):** An **abstract interface** that declares the construction steps (`buildPartA()`, `buildPartB()`...).
- **ConcreteBuilder (`ConcreteBuilder`):** The concrete implementation that **assembles** the parts and keeps track of the current representation. It provides a method like `getResult()` to retrieve the final product.
- **Director (`Director`):** The orchestrator. It holds a reference to a `Builder` and calls the construction steps in a **specific sequence** to enforce a valid configuration.
- **Client:** Triggers the whole thing by creating a `Director` and a `ConcreteBuilder`, then passing the builder to the director.

---

## 1.4 Why Builder? The "Telescoping Constructor" Problem

Consider constructing an `Employee` object with 10 optional fields:
- `name` (mandatory)
- `email` (mandatory)
- `phone` (optional)
- `address` (optional)
- `department` (optional)
- `salary` (optional)
- `role` (optional)
- `joiningDate` (optional)
- `manager` (optional)
- `cabinNumber` (optional)

A naive approach requires **2¹⁰ = 1024 constructors**! 🐛 This is the *Telescoping Constructor Anti-Pattern*.

> [!CAUTION]
> **Anti-Pattern Alert:** Constructor explosion, inconsistent state, unreadable client code. The Builder pattern eliminates this entirely.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 The "Why" — Motivation Behind Builder

The Builder pattern is used when:

1. **The construction algorithm should be independent of the parts being assembled.**
2. **The construction process must allow different representations** of the constructed object.
3. **Object construction involves many optional parameters** (avoids telescoping constructors).
4. **Step-by-step construction is required** — parts must be built in a specific order.

---

## 2.2 The Four Participants (Structured Logic Breakdown)

### Step 1 — Declare the `Builder` Abstract Interface
It declares product-specific construction steps. These are the *partial* building operations.

```text
Builder (Abstract Class / Interface)
   ├── buildPartA() : void
   ├── buildPartB() : void
   ├── buildPartC() : void
   └── getResult()  : Product
```

### Step 2 — Implement One or More `ConcreteBuilder` Classes
Each `ConcreteBuilder` provides a **different implementation** of the building steps. It also maintains an internal representation of the product being assembled.

```text
HawaiianBuilder implements Builder
   ├── private Product pizza;
   ├── buildPartA()  { pizza.setCrust("Thin"); }
   ├── buildPartB()  { pizza.setSize("Medium"); }
   ├── buildPartC()  { pizza.setToppings("Mushroom, Olives"); }
   └── getResult()   { return pizza; }
```

### Step 3 — The `Director` Orchestrates the Sequence
The Director does **not know** about the ConcreteBuilder type. It only knows the abstract Builder interface.

```text
Director
   ├── private Builder builder;
   ├── construct() {
   │      builder.buildPartA();   // Step order is fixed here
   │      builder.buildPartB();
   │      builder.buildPartC();
   │  }
```

### Step 4 — The `Client` Glues It All Together
The Client creates a `ConcreteBuilder` instance, hands it to a `Director`, triggers construction, and retrieves the `Product`.

---

## 2.3 KTU Reference Cheat Sheet

| Component | Role | Method Signature Pattern | Knowledge Required For KTU |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Product** | The complex object being built | `getPart1()`, `getPart2()` | UML Class Diagram |
| **Builder** | Abstract construction steps | `virtual buildPartA() = 0;` | Multiplicity (1 to 1) |
| **ConcreteBuilder** | Assembles parts, holds representation | `buildPartA() override { ... }` | Class inheritance arrow |
| **Director** | Calls builder in a sequence | `void construct(Builder b)` | Aggregation with Builder |
| **Client** | Wires everything up | `main()` / `AssemblyTest` | Optional to draw |

---

## 2.4 KTU Comparison: Builder vs Other Creational Patterns

> [!TIP]
> **Most Repeated KTU Question:** *"Differentiate between Builder, Abstract Factory, and Factory Method patterns."* (This appears in nearly every previous year KTU paper.)

| Criterion | **Builder** | **Abstract Factory** | **Factory Method** |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Focus** | Step-by-step construction | Family of related objects | Single object creation |
| **Complexity** | High (complex objects) | Medium (families) | Low (single product) |
| **Key Method** | `buildPartA()` + `getResult()` | `createProductA()`, `createProductB()` | `factoryMethod()` |
| **Object Returned** | Final assembled product | Family of products | One product |
| **Director Present?** | **Yes** | No | No |
| **KTU Tag** | *"Build it step-by-step"* | *"Family of related"* | *"Defer to subclass"* |

---

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Java's `StringBuilder` / `StringBuffer`** — appends characters step-by-step, then `.toString()`.
- **Java's `Stream.Builder`** — accumulates stream elements.
- **C#'s `StringBuilder`, `UriBuilder`**.
- **PDF/Document generation libraries** (e.g., iText) — building a PDF page-by-page.
- **SQL Query Builders** (e.g., jOOQ, Hibernate Criteria API).
- **Test data builders** in JUnit/TestNG for constructing complex test fixtures.

---

## 2.6 Variations of Builder (Bonus High-Yield Content)

1. **Classic GoF Builder** (Director + Builder hierarchy) — what KTU asks.
2. **Fluent Builder (Method Chaining)** — `new Pizza.Builder().setCrust("Thin").setSize("M").build();`
3. **Static Inner Class Builder** (Joshua Bloch's Effective Java style) — most common in modern Java.
4. **Builder with Lombok (`@Builder`)** — annotation-driven.

> [!NOTE]
> For KTU 2024 Scheme, the **Classic GoF Builder with Director** is the expected answer format. The Fluent style may fetch bonus marks if explained correctly.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Worked Example: Building a `House` (Classic KTU Problem)

This is the **single most common KTU exam problem** on the Builder pattern. We will derive the complete solution step-by-step.

### Step 1 — Define the `Product` Class

The Product is the complex object being built. A `House` has walls, roof, doors, windows, and a swimming pool (optional luxury).

```java
// ===== STEP 1: Product =====
public class House {
    private String walls;
    private String roof;
    private String doors;
    private String windows;
    private boolean hasSwimmingPool;
    private boolean hasGarden;
    private boolean hasGarage;

    public void setWalls(String walls)              { this.walls = walls; }
    public void setRoof(String roof)                { this.roof = roof; }
    public void setDoors(String doors)              { this.doors = doors; }
    public void setWindows(String windows)          { this.windows = windows; }
    public void setSwimmingPool(boolean b)          { this.hasSwimmingPool = b; }
    public void setGarden(boolean b)                { this.hasGarden = b; }
    public void setGarage(boolean b)                { this.hasGarage = b; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "House [walls=" + walls + ", roof=" + roof +
               ", doors=" + doors + ", windows=" + windows +
               ", pool=" + hasSwimmingPool +
               ", garden=" + hasGarden +
               ", garage=" + hasGarage + "]";
    }
}
```

> **Explanation of Step 1:** We define `House` as a plain POJO (Plain Old Java Object) with 7 fields. All setter methods are present so that the `ConcreteBuilder` can populate them. Note: there is **no public constructor** that takes all 7 arguments — this is intentional and demonstrates the *Builder's value*.

---

### Step 2 — Define the Abstract `Builder` Interface

```java
// ===== STEP 2: Abstract Builder =====
public abstract class HouseBuilder {
    protected House house;

    public House getHouse()           { return this.house; }

    public abstract void buildWalls();
    public abstract void buildRoof();
    public abstract void buildDoors();
    public abstract void buildWindows();
    public abstract void buildSwimmingPool();
    public abstract void buildGarden();
    public abstract void buildGarage();
}
```

> **Explanation of Step 2:** This is the **abstract builder**. It declares the partial construction steps. It also holds a `protected` `House` instance which will be instantiated by concrete builders.

---

### Step 3 — Implement `ConcreteBuilder` Classes

We will create two concrete builders: a **Wooden House Builder** and a **Brick House Builder**.

```java
// ===== STEP 3a: Wooden House Builder =====
public class WoodenHouseBuilder extends HouseBuilder {
    public WoodenHouseBuilder() { this.house = new House(); }

    @Override public void buildWalls()       { house.setWalls("Wooden Planks"); }
    @Override public void buildRoof()        { house.setRoof("Wooden Shingles"); }
    @Override public void buildDoors()       { house.setDoors("Pine Wood Door"); }
    @Override public void buildWindows()     { house.setWindows("Glass Panes"); }
    @Override public void buildSwimmingPool(){ house.setSwimmingPool(false); }
    @Override public void buildGarden()      { house.setGarden(true); }
    @Override public void buildGarage()      { house.setGarage(false); }
}

// ===== STEP 3b: Brick House Builder =====
public class BrickHouseBuilder extends HouseBuilder {
    public BrickHouseBuilder() { this.house = new House(); }

    @Override public void buildWalls()       { house.setWalls("Red Bricks"); }
    @Override public void buildRoof()        { house.setRoof("Concrete Slab"); }
    @Override public void buildDoors()       { house.setDoors("Steel Door"); }
    @Override public void buildWindows()     { house.setWindows("Double-Glazed Glass"); }
    @Override public void buildSwimmingPool(){ house.setSwimmingPool(true); }
    @Override public void buildGarden()      { house.setGarden(true); }
    @Override public void buildGarage()      { house.setGarage(true); }
}
```

> **Explanation of Step 3:** Each `ConcreteBuilder` makes its **own decisions** about how the parts are filled. Notice the *same* Director sequence will yield *different* Houses depending on which builder is plugged in. This is the **essence** of the Builder pattern.

---

### Step 4 — Implement the `Director`

```java
// ===== STEP 4: Director =====
public class ConstructionEngineer {
    private HouseBuilder houseBuilder;

    public ConstructionEngineer(HouseBuilder hb) { this.houseBuilder = hb; }

    public House constructHouse() {
        houseBuilder.buildWalls();
        houseBuilder.buildRoof();
        houseBuilder.buildDoors();
        houseBuilder.buildWindows();
        houseBuilder.buildSwimmingPool();
        houseBuilder.buildGarden();
        houseBuilder.buildGarage();
        return houseBuilder.getHouse();
    }
}
```

> **Explanation of Step 4:** The Director **enforces the order** of construction. Walls first, then roof, then doors, etc. The Director only knows about the abstract `HouseBuilder` — it does **not** know whether it is dealing with a `WoodenHouseBuilder` or a `BrickHouseBuilder`.

---

### Step 5 — The `Client` (Main Method)

```java
// ===== STEP 5: Client =====
public class ClientMain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Build a wooden house
        HouseBuilder woodenBuilder = new WoodenHouseBuilder();
        ConstructionEngineer engineer1 = new ConstructionEngineer(woodenBuilder);
        House woodenHouse = engineer1.constructHouse();
        System.out.println("Wooden House: " + woodenHouse);

        // Build a brick house
        HouseBuilder brickBuilder = new BrickHouseBuilder();
        ConstructionEngineer engineer2 = new ConstructionEngineer(brickBuilder);
        House brickHouse = engineer2.constructHouse();
        System.out.println("Brick House:  " + brickHouse);
    }
}
```

### Step 6 — Expected Output Trace

```text
Wooden House: House [walls=Wooden Planks, roof=Wooden Shingles, doors=Pine Wood Door,
                     windows=Glass Panes, pool=false, garden=true, garage=false]
Brick House:  House [walls=Red Bricks, roof=Concrete Slab, doors=Steel Door,
                     windows=Double-Glazed Glass, pool=true, garden=true, garage=true]
```

---

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix: Mapping Code → UML Components

| Java Class | UML Role | Visibility in Class Diagram | KTU Drawing Convention |
|---|---|---|---|
| `House` | **Product** | Normal class rectangle | No stereotype |
| `HouseBuilder` | **Builder** | Abstract class with `<<abstract>>` | Italic method names |
| `WoodenHouseBuilder` | **ConcreteBuilder** | Inherits from `HouseBuilder` | Hollow triangle arrow |
| `BrickHouseBuilder` | **ConcreteBuilder** | Inherits from `HouseBuilder` | Hollow triangle arrow |
| `ConstructionEngineer` | **Director** | Holds ref to `HouseBuilder` | Aggregation (empty diamond) |
| `ClientMain` | **Client** | (Usually omitted in KTU diagrams) | Dashed line / omitted |

---

## 3.3 Collaboration Sequence (Step-by-Step Walkthrough)

The following numbered sequence is what KTU examiners expect when a question asks *"Explain the collaborations between participants."*

1. The **Client** creates a `ConcreteBuilder` object.
2. The **Client** creates a `Director` and configures it with the new `ConcreteBuilder`.
3. The **Director** notifies the builder whenever a part of the product should be built.
4. The **Builder** handles requests from the Director and **adds parts to the product**.
5. The **Client** retrieves the product from the builder.

> [!NOTE]
> The Director is only required because KTU follows the **classic GoF** definition. In modern fluent builders (e.g., Lombok `@Builder`), the Director role is often absorbed into the Client.

---

## 3.4 Consequences (Pros & Cons — High-Yield KTU Points)

| **Advantages (Marks-scoring)** | **Disadvantages (Mention for full marks)** |
|---|---|
| ✅ Lets you vary the product's internal representation | ❌ Increases total number of classes (verbosity) |
| ✅ Isolates code for construction and representation | ❌ Not suitable for simple objects |
| ✅ Finer control over the construction process | ❌ Overkill when the object has < 4 fields |
| ✅ Avoids the telescoping constructor anti-pattern | ❌ Builder classes must be **mutable** internally |
| ✅ Single Director can produce many representations | ❌ Steeper learning curve for new developers |
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
# SECTION 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 UML Class Diagram (Builder Pattern – Classic GoF)

The following Mermaid class diagram captures the **complete GoF Builder pattern structure** with the House example.

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Client {
        +main()
    }

    class Director {
        -HouseBuilder builder
        +constructHouse() House
    }

    class HouseBuilder {
        <<abstract>>
        #House house
        +getHouse() House
        +buildWalls() void
        +buildRoof() void
        +buildDoors() void
        +buildWindows() void
        +buildSwimmingPool() void
        +buildGarden() void
        +buildGarage() void
    }

    class WoodenHouseBuilder {
        +buildWalls() void
        +buildRoof() void
        +buildDoors() void
        +buildWindows() void
        +buildSwimmingPool() void
        +buildGarden() void
        +buildGarage() void
    }

    class BrickHouseBuilder {
        +buildWalls() void
        +buildRoof() void
        +buildDoors() void
        +buildWindows() void
        +buildSwimmingPool() void
        +buildGarden() void
        +buildGarage() void
    }

    class House {
        -String walls
        -String roof
        -String doors
        -String windows
        -boolean hasSwimmingPool
        -boolean hasGarden
        -boolean hasGarage
        +setWalls(String) void
        +setRoof(String) void
        +setDoors(String) void
        +setWindows(String) void
        +setSwimmingPool(boolean) void
        +setGarden(boolean) void
        +setGarage(boolean) void
        +toString() String
    }

    Client --> Director : creates
    Client --> WoodenHouseBuilder : creates
    Client --> BrickHouseBuilder : creates
    Director o-- HouseBuilder : aggregates
    HouseBuilder <|-- WoodenHouseBuilder : extends
    HouseBuilder <|-- BrickHouseBuilder : extends
    WoodenHouseBuilder ..> House : builds
    BrickHouseBuilder ..> House : builds
```

**Diagram Reading Guide (KTU Examiner's Checklist):**
- **Solid line with hollow triangle** → Inheritance (`HouseBuilder` → `WoodenHouseBuilder`).
- **Solid line with empty diamond (`o--`)** → Aggregation (Director has-a Builder).
- **Dashed line with arrow (`..>`)** → Dependency / builds (ConcreteBuilder creates a `House`).
- **Italic method names** in `HouseBuilder` indicate **abstract** methods.

---

## 4.2 Sequence Diagram (Object Interaction Flow)

This Mermaid sequence diagram shows the **runtime interactions** for constructing a Brick House.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    actor Client
    participant Director
    participant BrickBuilder
    participant House

    Client->>BrickBuilder: new BrickHouseBuilder()
    Client->>Director: new ConstructionEngineer(builder)
    Client->>Director: constructHouse()

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildWalls()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setWalls("Red Bricks")

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildRoof()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setRoof("Concrete Slab")

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildDoors()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setDoors("Steel Door")

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildWindows()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setWindows("Double-Glazed Glass")

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildSwimmingPool()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setSwimmingPool(true)

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildGarden()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setGarden(true)

    Director->>BrickBuilder: buildGarage()
    BrickBuilder->>House: setGarage(true)

    Director->>BrickBuilder: getHouse()
    BrickBuilder-->>Director: returns House object
    Director-->>Client: returns fully built House
```

---

## 4.3 Functional Architecture Flow (Block Diagram)

If a **physical drawing** is not feasible in the answer sheet, KTU examiners accept a **block-level flow diagram** of the same structure:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Client Main Method] --> B[Instantiate ConcreteBuilder]
    B --> C[Instantiate Director with Builder]
    C --> D[Director.constructHouse]
    D --> E[Builder.buildWalls]
    D --> F[Builder.buildRoof]
    D --> G[Builder.buildDoors]
    D --> H[Builder.buildWindows]
    D --> I[Builder.buildSwimmingPool]
    D --> J[Builder.buildGarden]
    D --> K[Builder.buildGarage]
    E --> L[Product - House]
    F --> L
    G --> L
    H --> L
    I --> L
    J --> L
    K --> L
    L --> M[getResult returns House]
    M --> N[Client receives final Product]
```

**Color/Shape Convention (optional in KTU):**
- Rectangles = Classes
- Rounded Rectangles = Methods/Operations
- Cylinders = Data/Product
