# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **KTU Pattern:** Each Part-A question is 3 marks. The answer should be **3–4 lines** with a **diagram** (if applicable). Avoid long essays.

---

### Question 1 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model Paper]**
> *What is the Builder Design Pattern? List its main participants.*

**Model Answer:**

The Builder Design Pattern is a **creational design pattern** that separates the construction of a complex object from its representation, so that the same construction process can create different representations.

The four main participants are:

1. **Product** — the complex object being constructed.
2. **Builder** — abstract interface declaring construction steps.
3. **ConcreteBuilder** — implements `Builder` and assembles the parts.
4. **Director** — orchestrates the construction sequence using a `Builder` reference.

> *(Draw a small block diagram with the 4 participants and their relationships for full 3 marks.)*

---

### Question 2 (3 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model Paper]**
> *When would you prefer the Builder pattern over the Factory pattern?*

**Model Answer:**

The Builder pattern is preferred over the Factory pattern when:

1. The object has **many optional parameters** (avoiding telescoping constructors).
2. The construction process must happen in a **specific step-by-step order**.
3. The same construction process should produce **different representations** of the product.
4. The product is **complex** with multiple interdependent parts.

Factory is used for creating **single, simple objects** with one-step creation, whereas Builder is used for **complex, multi-part objects** requiring step-by-step assembly.

---

## 5.2 PART B — Full-Descriptive Questions (14 Marks Each)

> **KTU Pattern:** Part B carries 14 marks. You may get **internal choice** — meaning the examiner offers Question A OR Question B. Both options are given below.

---

### ⭐ QUESTION A (14 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model Paper]**

> *(a)* Explain the Builder Design Pattern with a neat UML class diagram. List its participants and their roles. *(7 marks)*
>
> *(b)* Write a Java program to demonstrate the Builder pattern for constructing a `Computer` object with components like `CPU`, `RAM`, `Storage`, `GraphicsCard`, and `Bluetooth` (optional). Use a `Director` to enforce the construction order. *(7 marks)*

---

#### ✅ Part (a) — Model Solution (7 marks)

**Definition (1 mark):**
The Builder pattern is a creational design pattern that **encapsulates the construction of a complex object** so that different representations can be produced using the **same construction process**.

**Participants and Roles (3 marks):**

| Participant | Role |
|---|---|
| `Product` | The complex object being built. |
| `Builder` | Abstract interface declaring build steps. |
| `ConcreteBuilder` | Implements Builder, assembles parts, holds representation, provides retrieval method. |
| `Director` | Calls Builder methods in a fixed sequence. |
| `Client` | Creates Director and ConcreteBuilder, retrieves product. |

**UML Class Diagram (3 marks):**
*(Refer to the class diagram in SECTION 4.1. Students must draw: abstract `Builder`, two `ConcreteBuilder` classes inheriting from it, `Director` aggregating `Builder`, and `ConcreteBuilder` depending on `Product`.)*

---

#### ✅ Part (b) — Model Solution (7 marks)

**Skeleton Code (write this in the answer sheet):**

```java
// PRODUCT
class Computer {
    private String CPU, RAM, storage, graphicsCard;
    private boolean hasBluetooth;
    // Setters...
    public String toString() { /* return component list */ }
}

// ABSTRACT BUILDER
abstract class ComputerBuilder {
    protected Computer computer = new Computer();
    public abstract void buildCPU();
    public abstract void buildRAM();
    public abstract void buildStorage();
    public abstract void buildGraphicsCard();
    public abstract void buildBluetooth();
    public Computer getComputer() { return computer; }
}

// CONCRETE BUILDER
class GamingPCBuilder extends ComputerBuilder {
    public void buildCPU()          { computer.setCPU("Intel i9"); }
    public void buildRAM()          { computer.setRAM("32GB DDR5"); }
    public void buildStorage()      { computer.setStorage("2TB SSD"); }
    public void buildGraphicsCard() { computer.setGraphicsCard("RTX 4090"); }
    public void buildBluetooth()    { computer.setBluetooth(true); }
}

// DIRECTOR
class ComputerEngineer {
    private ComputerBuilder builder;
    public ComputerEngineer(ComputerBuilder b) { this.builder = b; }
    public Computer assemble() {
        builder.buildCPU();
        builder.buildRAM();
        builder.buildStorage();
        builder.buildGraphicsCard();
        builder.buildBluetooth();
        return builder.getComputer();
    }
}

// CLIENT
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ComputerBuilder gamingBuilder = new GamingPCBuilder();
        ComputerEngineer engineer = new ComputerEngineer(gamingBuilder);
        Computer pc = engineer.assemble();
        System.out.println("Gaming PC: " + pc);
    }
}
```

**Mark Distribution for (b):**
- Product class with getters/setters → **1 mark**
- Abstract Builder with method declarations → **1.5 marks**
- ConcreteBuilder with overrides → **2 marks**
- Director class with `assemble()` method → **1.5 marks**
- Client `main()` showing wiring → **1 mark**

---

### ⭐ QUESTION B (14 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model Paper]**

> *(a)* Compare and contrast the **Builder Pattern** with the **Abstract Factory Pattern** in terms of intent, structure, and use cases. *(7 marks)*
>
> *(b)* *"The Builder pattern is useful when the algorithm for creating a complex object should be independent of the parts that make up the object."* Discuss this statement and explain the consequences (advantages & disadvantages) of using the Builder pattern. *(7 marks)*

---

#### ✅ Part (a) — Model Solution (7 marks)

| Criterion | **Builder Pattern** | **Abstract Factory Pattern** |
|---|---|---|
| **Intent** | Step-by-step construction of a complex object | Family of related/dependent objects |
| **Focus** | Building *one* complex product piece by piece | Producing *multiple* related products |
| **Key Methods** | `buildPartA()`, `getResult()` | `createProductA()`, `createProductB()` |
| **Director Role** | **Yes** (orchestrates construction order) | **No** (client directly calls factory) |
| **Use Case** | Document, House, Pizza construction | UI Toolkit (Button + Textbox + Checkbox family) |
| **Complexity** | High | Medium |
| **Returned Object** | Single complex product after assembly | Multiple related products |

**Conclusion (1 mark):** Builder is for *one complex product built step-by-step*; Abstract Factory is for *a family of related products built at once*.

---

#### ✅ Part (b) — Model Solution (7 marks)

**Discussion (3 marks):**
The statement is the textbook **GoF definition** of the Builder pattern. The *algorithm* (the sequence of `buildPartX()` calls) is locked inside the **Director**, while the *parts* (the actual values being set) are determined by the **ConcreteBuilder**. This decoupling means you can plug in any new `ConcreteBuilder` (e.g., `IglooBuilder`, `TreehouseBuilder`) without touching the Director code. The Director doesn't know *what* is being built — only *how the steps should proceed*.

**Advantages (2.5 marks):**
- Varies product representation internally.
- Isolates construction code from representation.
- Finer control over the construction steps.
- Avoids telescoping constructor anti-pattern.

**Disadvantages (1.5 marks):**
- Increases total number of classes in the system.
- Verbose for simple objects (overkill for < 4 fields).
- Requires mutable builder objects internally.

